    pearls: ["Rhonchi that clear with coughing are a key distinguishing feature - always reassess breath sounds after having the patient cough and document the change.", "When reporting rhonchi to the RN, describe the specific location (which lung fields), timing (inspiratory, expiratory, or both), and whether they changed with coughing or repositioning.", "Do not confuse rhonchi with stridor. Stridor is a high-pitched sound heard primarily on inspiration and indicates upper airway obstruction - this is a medical emergency requiring immediate intervention.", "Positioning is a powerful nursing intervention for rhonchi. Elevating the head of bed and turning the patient to different positions uses gravity to assist with secretion drainage from affected lung segments.", "Patients who are post-operative, immobile, or have neuromuscular weakness are at highest risk for developing rhonchi because they cannot cough effectively to clear normal airway secretions."],
    quiz: [{ question: "An RPN auscultates low-pitched, continuous, snoring-like sounds over a patient's right lower lung field. After asking the patient to cough, the sounds are no longer heard in that area. How should the nurse document and report this finding?", options: ["Document as wheezing in the right lower lobe that resolved spontaneously", "Document as rhonchi in the right lower lobe that cleared with coughing and report to the RN", "Document as crackles in the right lower lobe and administer a bronchodilator", "Document as normal breath sounds since the sounds resolved"], correct: 1, rationale: "Low-pitched, continuous, snoring-like sounds are characteristic of rhonchi - not wheezing (which is high-pitched) or crackles (which are discontinuous popping sounds). A hallmark feature of rhonchi is that they may clear or change after coughing, because coughing mobilizes the secretions in the large airways that produce the sound. The nurse should accurately document the finding as rhonchi, note the specific location (right lower lobe), and report that they cleared with coughing. This information helps the nurse and healthcare team assess the patient's respiratory status and determine if further interventions are needed. The sounds should not be documented as normal simply because they resolved - the initial finding is clinically significant." }]
